                  <p align="left"><b><a href="http://webpublisher.lexisnexis.com/index.asp?layout=story&gid=1170000917&cid=310004031&did=47JT-7G30-0002-P19X-00000-00&b=s"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Former 
                    BOC Branch Chief Jailed for Life </font></a></b></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">(China) 
                    - A former chief of Bank of China's Zhanjiang branch received 
                    a life sentence from a Guangdong court last week for corruption 
                    and financial malpractice, state media said. </font><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Fan 
                    Shaorun, 55, headed BOC's Zhanjiang branch between August 
                    1993 and June 1996. The court found him to have embezzled 
                    HK$ 650,000 of bank funds during his tenure and misallocated 
                    32.1 million yuan (about HK$ 30.07 million). </font></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="http://webpublisher.lexisnexis.com/index.asp?layout=story&gid=1170000917&did=47K0-VGF0-0049-X4CY-00000-00&cid=310004031&b=s"><b>Tyco 
                    Acknowledges More Accounting Tricks, Also Divulges More Extravagant 
                    Expenses </b></a> </font></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Scandal-racked 
                    Tyco International used aggressive accounting to inflate its 
                    2002 results by nearly $ 400 million and relied on accounting 
                    gimmicks to boost its financial reports over the last five 
                    years, the company said Monday. Tyco said the findings, the 
                    result of a long-awaited internal review of its accounting 
                    and corporate governance, would force the company to take 
                    $ 382.2 million in charges for its 2002 fiscal year beyond 
                    the $ 2.8 billion announced earlier this year. However, Tyco 
                    stressed that the unusual review did not uncover signs of 
                    &quot;systemic or significant fraud&quot; that would significantly 
                    reduce earnings and cash flow for 2003 and beyond.</font></p>
