              <tr> 
                <td> 
                  <div align="left"></div>
                  <table width="100" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
                    <tr> 
                      <td bgcolor="#FFFFCC"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="2" color="#000000"><b>FRAUD 
                        TIPS</b></font></td>
                    </tr>
                  </table>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Bulletin 
                    Boards</b></font></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Bulletin 
                    boards are a popular medium on the Internet where investors 
                    share information regarding various investment opportunities. 
                    Fraudsters use these bulletin boards to &quot;pump up&quot; 
                    a company or pretend to divulge &quot;inside&quot; information. 
                    Bulletin boards allow users to hide their identity behind 
                    multiple aliases making it very difficult to distinguish whether 
                    the message is true or fraudulent. The message may be from 
                    a company insider, large shareholder, or paid promoter although 
                    they claim to be an unbiased observer. </font></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Junk e-mail 
                    or spam enables fraudsters to send personalized messages to 
                    millions of Internet users for bogus investment schemes or 
                    disseminate false information regarding a company, targeting 
                    more potential investors than cold calling or mass mailing.</font></p>
                  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Source: 
                    <a href="http://marketplace.cfenet.com/products/ProductDetail.asp?ProdID=316"><i>Investment 
                    Swindles &amp; Con Schemes</i></a>, a NEW self-study video/workbook 
                    course from the Association of Certified Fraud Examiners.</font> 
                  </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
